BugPattern.ShortDescription: Bad comparison of int value with long constant

BugPattern.ShortDescription: Call to equals() comparing different types
BugPattern.Details: This method calls equals(Object) on two references of different class types and analysis suggests they will be to objects of different classes at runtime. Further, examination of the equals methods that would be invoked suggest that either this call will always return false, or else the equals method is not be symmetric (which is a property required by the contract for equals in class Object).

BugPattern.ShortDescription: Using pointer equality to compare different types
BugPattern.Details: This method uses using pointer equality to compare two references that seem to be of different types. The result of this comparison will always be false at runtime.

BugPattern.ShortDescription: Method with Boolean return type returns explicit null
BugPattern.Details: A method that returns either Boolean.TRUE, Boolean.FALSE or null is an accident waiting to happen. This method can be invoked as though it returned a value of type boolean, and the compiler will insert automatic unboxing of the Boolean value. If a null value is returned, this will result in a NullPointerException.
